 settling on adding a public `new_for_testing` constructor to both adapters that accepts a custom reqwest client, marked with `#[allow(dead_code)]` since it won't be used in the library itself but will be available for integration tests. I'm adding a hidden testing constructor that accepts a custom `reqwest::Client`, which lets me inject a client with specific timeout behavior for testing without exposing it as part of the public API. I need to make sure `AnthropicCompatClient` also supports this pattern so the timeout test can actually verify the error handling. Adding test constructors...\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. I only need a single way to inject a custom HTTP client for testing timeouts—I don't need to add `new_for_testing` to every adapter. The inline module tests already cover the timeout mapping logic, so I just need the acceptance test to call through with a custom client. Let me stick with the minimal approach of adding `new_with_http_client` to the internal client types.\n\nLooking at how `OpenRouterAdapter` wraps `OpenAiCompatAdapter`, I can follow that same pattern and add a `new_for_testing` method that accepts a custom HTTP client. Now I'm ready to write the actual code—I'll create the contract test file and implement the necessary constructor methods. I need to add `new_for_testing` to the OpenRouter adapter as well, then start writing the contract tests. For those tests, I can directly instantiate the wire format types like `AnthropicRequest` and verify the field mappings without relying on integration tests, which gives me more direct control over testing the serialization contracts. Writing contract tests... Writing test assertions... Writing test assertions... Writing test cases... Writing test assertions... Writing test assertions... I'm looking at how the function filters text blocks and joins them with newlines, which should produce the expected concatenated output. Now I'm thinking through the integration tests using wiremock to