{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GWaUDvP9zEGXjwXqNpHv3e","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a full picture. Let me design the test suite.\n\nThe key things I need:\n1. Add `wiremock` as a dev-dependency to `crates/provider/Cargo.toml`\n2. Create test files that cover all acceptance criteria\n\nFor AC1/AC2 (LlmRequest round-trip), since I need to test through the actual adapter, I'll use wiremock to capture requests and verify wire format. I'll also add `#[cfg(test)]` constructors to allow injecting a custom reqwest::Client for timeout testing.\n\nWait - for timeout testing, I have a problem: the existing constructors use `reqwest::Client::new()` which doesn't have a timeout. I need to either:\n\n\n1. Add a `#[cfg(test)]` helper that creates the client with a timeout\n2. Or just test the error mapping function directly\n\nLooking at the code structure, the `map_reqwest_error` function is private to each client module. From an integration test, I can verify timeout behavior by using a real slow server or creating a custom reqwest client with a timeout. But the clients don't expose a way to set the timeout, so I'll add a `#[cfg(test)]` helper to both clients for testing with a custom client—this is a minimal code change.\n\nLet me think about what \"network timeout\" means in the context of this test. The criterion says the error should be properly mapped when a timeout occurs.\n\nThe implementation already handles this with a function that checks if the error is a timeout and returns `LlmError::Timeout`, otherwise it returns a network error. This function is private to the module, so it's tested in the inline unit tests but not exposed to the external test files.\n\nFor the acceptance test suite, I can either expose a public version of the error mapper for testing or test it at the integration level with a real timeout.\n\nLooking at this more practically for integration tests, I could use wiremock to create a server that never responds, then pair it with a custom reqwest client that has a short timeout like 100ms. To make this work, I'd need to add test-only constructors to both clients that accept a custom client. The simplest approach is probably adding `#[cfg(test)]` constructors rather than a separate feature flag.\n\nBut there's a complication—`AnthropicCompatClient` is `pub(crate)`, so integration tests can't access it directly. I need to reconsider what's actually testable from the external test scope and whether I should be testing through the public adapters instead.\n\nLooking at what's accessible: `AnthropicAdapter` and `OpenRouterAdapter` are public, but `OpenAiCompatAdapter` is private. For the timeout test, I could add a test helper to the public adapters that accepts a custom client, though that would require refactoring how they currently instantiate their internal clients. This is getting complicated, so let me try a simpler approach and just test the timeout behavior through the public adapter interface.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this. I should check what tests already exist inline in the modules—there are already tests for 400 errors, 429 retries, and stream event ordering. Let me see what else is already covered before adding new ones. I'm looking at the remaining acceptance tests I need to write—integration tests for both adapters' complete and stream methods, tool use flows, error handling for auth and network issues, and end-to-end scenarios like agent loops and provider switching. My approach is to set up wiremock for mocking HTTP responses and create a new acceptance test module that covers all these cases systematically.\n\nFor the round-trip tests, I'm thinking of them as verifying that an LlmRequest gets properly serialized into the correct wire format when sent to each provider—I can capture the actual request body with wiremock and validate its structure. On the timeout side, I'll need to inject a custom reqwest client into the adapters during testing to simulate network delays without actually waiting. I'm realizing the timeout test just needs to verify that `LlmError::Timeout` gets returned when a network timeout occurs, and the cleanest approach is adding a `#[cfg(test)]` constructor to inject a custom client with a short timeout pointing to a server that delays responses.\n\nFor the implementation, I'll add test-only `with_client()` constructors to the client types and bring in `wiremock` for mocking HTTP responses, though tokio is already available in the workspace dependencies. I need to set up dev-dependencies with the right tokio features for testing, then create three test files covering contract logic, HTTP integration, and agent loop behavior. For the contract tests, I'll construct `AnthropicRequest` objects that match what `build_body` would produce, serialize them to JSON to verify all fields are present, and validate round-trip deserialization works correctly.\n\nWait—I'm realizing there are actually two different `AnthropicRequest` structs in the codebase. One in `compat::request` handles the wire-to-wire conversion between Anthropic and OpenAI formats, while the other in `anthropic_compat::types` represents the actual Anthropic API wire format that gets sent to their servers. I need to test against the second one since that's what actually gets serialized and transmitted.\n\nThe problem is that `anthropic_compat` is private to the crate, so I can't access it from external tests. The right approach here is to use wiremock—I'll set up a mock Anthropic server, call `complete()` with a specific `LlmRequest`, and then verify that the captured request body has the correct Anthropic wire format structure. This way I'm testing the actual conversion without needing direct access to the internal types.\n\nSetting up the integration test... Writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm mapping out the complete test suite structure with four contract tests covering the Anthropic and OpenAI wire formats, tool schema mapping, and stop reason conversions.\n\nActually, I should split this differently—the wire format tests need wiremock to capture actual HTTP requests, so those belong in integration tests instead. The contract tests should focus on pure logic: tool definition bijection, stop reason bidirectional mapping, and streaming event ordering for both providers. Then integration tests will handle the actual adapter methods with mocked HTTP responses.\n\nFor the remaining test cases covering error handling and the agent loop, I'm planning to use pure logic tests with a mock LlmClient to verify provider switching works without code changes. I also need to handle timeout testing by injecting a custom reqwest client into the adapters, and I'm realizing the Anthropic adapter will need the base URL configured correctly for wiremock to intercept the requests properly. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to add test-only constructors directly to `AnthropicCompatClient` and `OpenAiCompatClient` that accept an injected `reqwest::Client`, allowing me to pass in a mocked HTTP client for the timeout test. I'm tracing through how the test would work: create a client with a 100ms timeout, pass it to the adapter, call complete, the mock server delays 1 second, and the request times out properly. Since `AnthropicCompatClient` is `pub(crate)`, I can access its test constructor from the adapter module. Now I need to plan out the code changes to add these test constructors to both the client and adapter.\n\nAdding test constructors...\n\nI realize `openai_compat` is private to the crate, so I can't use it for integration tests—I'll add the helper to `OpenRouterAdapter` instead. Then I need to update the `Cargo.toml` to include the necessary dev dependencies.\n\nNow I'm setting up the test infrastructure with wiremock to mock HTTP responses and tokio for async test execution.\n\nFor the contract tests, I'll focus on the ones that don't require HTTP mocking—the bijection tests for ToolDefinition and StopReason mapping, plus the streaming event ordering tests that work directly with the internal conversion functions.\n\nSince those conversion functions are private, I can't call them from external test files, so I'll test the streaming event ordering at the integration level instead. I'll set up a mock SSE server that sends events in a specific sequence, call the adapter's stream method, collect the events, and verify they arrive in the correct order. This gives me both a proper test and integration coverage.\n\nLooking at what needs testing, the existing inline tests already partially cover some acceptance criteria like stream ordering and retry-after extraction, but those are unit tests of private functions. The acceptance criteria specifically require integration tests that exercise the full adapter pipeline end-to-end with a mock HTTP server, so I need to build out a comprehensive test suite in an external test file that validates the complete flow. Finishing up the error handling cases, then moving into the agent loop tests. Now I need to check the exact SSE format for both Anthropic and OpenAI to make sure the streaming integration tests capture the right event sequences. I'm realizing that wiremock can return the full SSE-formatted body as a string with the proper `Content-Type: text/event-stream` header, and even though it won't stream the bytes incrementally, the reqwest client's line-by-line parsing should still work correctly since the body contains the necessary newlines.\n\nNow I need to write out all the tests, starting with the agent loop tests. For AC16, I'm creating a mock `LlmClient` that simulates a two-turn interaction where the first call returns tool calls and the second call returns a final response after the tool executes, verifying that everything stays within the canonical types from `ccode_ports::provider`.\n\nWriting the test implementation... I'm realizing there's a mismatch in th