facts.\n\nFor the SSE streaming tests, I need to cover the full Anthropic event sequence: message_start with token counts, content_block_start for different block types, the various delta events for text and tool input, content_block_stop, message_delta, and message_stop. Let me map out what a text response stream should look like. Now I'm looking at how the SSE response changes when a tool is being invoked instead of just returning text—the message includes a tool_use content block with an id and name, and the deltas stream the tool's input parameters as JSON rather than plain text. I'm looking at SSE streaming responses for both text and tool calls, seeing how the delta payloads build up the content incrementally. Now I need to write the actual test code, keeping in mind the API key header requirement, careful float comparison for request bodies, proper newline formatting for streaming responses, and a delayed server response for the timeout test.\n\nFor the dev dependencies, I'll need to add wiremock and configure tokio with the right features for async tests and multi-threaded runtime support. Then I'll organize the test files logically and start writing them out.\n\nI can write tests directly for the public adapters and wiremock-based response parsing without any code changes, but the timeout test will need a workaround. Instead of modifying the adapter constructors, I can use tokio's timeout utility to wrap the adapter call and verify it completes within the expected window. the adapters to support test-specific client construction. I could wrap the request in a `tokio::time::timeout` within the adapter, but that changes production behavior. A feature flag approach would work but feels like polluting the codebase for testing purposes. The cleanest solution is adding `#[cfg(test)]` constructors—it's a standard Rust pattern and keeps test code isolated.\n\nNow I'm actually writing the implementation. I'll add the dev dependencies and create test helper construct