ify it alternates between completing requests and executing tool calls. Still writing test logic... I'm working through the trait bounds for the test client—`FixedResponseClient` needs to be `Send + Sync` for the `async_trait`, and since it wraps an `Arc<Mutex<VecDeque<...>>>`, I need to verify the inner types satisfy those bounds. The stream type is already `Send`, so this should compile, though I'm second-guessing whether to use `std::sync::Mutex` or `tokio::sync::Mutex` in an async context.\n\nWriting the helper method... I need to use `futures::stream::iter()` since `tokio-stream` isn't available in the provider crate's dependencies, and I can wrap the vector of stream events in a pinned box to create the proper `LlmStream` type. For the AC17 test, I'm setting up a helper function that takes a client and messages, then runs a single turn to extract the response text and tool calls.\n\nWriting the test function... Writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm thinking through the scope—the existing tests already cover a lot, so I should figure out what's actually missing before writing more code.\n\nLooking at the acceptance criteria, I need to add serialization tests for both Anthropic and OpenAI wire formats in the contract tests, extend the schema mapping and stop reason tests, verify streaming event ordering end-to-end, and create new integration tests for the adapter methods to ensure they send valid requests and yield correct sequences.\n\nFor error handling, I'll add integration tests covering authentication failures, rate limiting, request size limits, malformed responses, and then test the agent loop and provider switching. For the timeout case, I'm considering using a very short reqwest timeout duration to trigger the condition without needing custom test infrastructure. I need to add test constructors to both the client and adapter so I can inject a custom reqwest client with a timeout configured, allowing me to properly test the timeout error handling path th