ture flag approach seems cleanest, though making it a regular public method is simpler if I'm willing to accept it being part of the public API. I'm realizing that features aren't automatically enabled for integration tests—they're compiled as separate crates that use the library without dev-dependencies. Let me step back and consider simpler approaches: either making the test constructor always public with a clearer name like `new_with_http_client`, using a dedicated `test` feature, or just relying on the unit tests already in the module instead of testing at the integration level.\n\nLooking at the Rust documentation more carefully, I see that `#[cfg(test)]` only applies to code within the library itself when running `cargo test`, but integration tests in the `tests/` directory are compiled separately—the library gets compiled in normal mode without the test flag, while the integration test binaries themselves have `--cfg test` applied to them. I'm realizing that integration tests compile the library without the `--cfg test` flag, so my `#[cfg(test)]` constructor won't be accessible to them. The cleanest solution is to remove the test-only attribute and rename the constructor to make its testing purpose clear.\n\nBut actually, I could test timeouts differently—maybe at the `OpenAiCompatClient` level using inline unit tests instead, which would let me keep the test-only constructor since those tests run within the crate where `#[cfg(test)]` is active.\n\nThe simplest fix though is to just remove the `#[cfg(test)]` attribute and make both constructors always public. The name `new_for_test` or `with_http_client` signals its purpose clearly enough without needing to hide it behind a compile flag. I'll go ahead and remove those attributes from both the `AnthropicCompatClient` and `AnthropicAdapter` constructors.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3538,"cache_read_input_to