{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AY2iqPNbhoWRMT3rjSyeXX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `anthropic_tool_use_flow_request_tool_result_final_answer` test is failing. The assertion says \"should receive exactly one tool call\" but got 0.\n\nThe issue is likely with the `up_to_n_times(1)` wiremock ordering. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, looking more carefully at wiremock's behavior: I said the last mounted mock has the highest priority. But let me re-check: I mount:\n1. Second response (final text) first\n2. First response (tool call) second with `up_to_n_times(1)`\n\n\nSo the second mount (tool call) should have higher priority and be used first.\n\nBut the test is failing with 0 tool calls received, which means the tool_call SSE isn't being returned for the first request. Let me examine the SSE body more carefully—the `anthropic_tool_call_sse()` function constructs the message_start event, then the content_block_start event with the tool_use type, followed by content_block_delta events...\n\nGenerating SSE response...\n\nActually, I think I see the problem now. When I serialize the `partial_json` field with `serde_json::json!()`, the nested JSON string gets escaped, so `{\"query\":\"rust\"}` becomes `\"{\\\"query\\\":\\\"rust\\\"}\"` in the output. When the Anthropic client parses this, it's reading `delta_type` as `\"input_json_delta\"` and `partial_json` as the escaped string, which might not be getting deserialized correctly downstream.\n\nLet me reconsider the wiremock mock matching order too—I think I had it backwards. In wiremock 0.6, mocks are matched in the order they were mounted, so the first matching mock wins, not the last one. So the issue is clear now—wiremock matches mocks in FIFO order, meaning the first mounted mock gets tried first. Since I mounted `final_text` before `tool_call`, every request matches `final_text` and `tool_call` never gets used. I need to reverse the mount order so `tool_call` (with its `up_to_n_times(1)` limit) is tried first, gets exhausted after one call, and then subsequent requests fall through to `final_text`. I need to verify that wiremock actually skips exhausted mocks and tries the next matching one—looking at the documentation, it does fall through to subsequent mocks once a limit is consumed. So my mount order is correct: tool_call first (limited to one use), then final_text as the fallback for subsequent requests.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":517,"cache_read_input_tokens":160041,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":517,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"33623158-75cc-4f67-b2ef-8a696211d978","uuid":"5551bb04-925d-48f9-beb4-ffb5083dc278"}
